# Chapter 6 - Storage

## Definition
Storage is the cornerstone of the data engineering lifecycle.
It underlies every stage — ingestion, transformation, and serving.
Data gets stored many times as it moves through the lifecycle.
Choosing the right storage means understanding your use case
and how you will retrieve the data in the future.

## Raw Ingredients of Storage

### Storage Hardware Comparison
| Type | Latency | Cost | Best For |
|---|---|---|---|
| CPU Cache | 1 nanosecond | Very expensive | Active CPU processing |
| RAM | 0.1 microseconds | ~$10/GB | Fast in-memory processing |
| SSD | 0.1 milliseconds | ~$0.20/GB | Transactional databases, OLTP |
| HDD | 4 milliseconds | ~$0.03/GB | Bulk storage, data lakes |
| Object Storage | 100 milliseconds | ~$0.02/GB/month | Data lakes, cloud warehouses |
| Archival Storage | 12 hours | ~$0.004/GB/month | Compliance, long-term backup |

### Key Raw Ingredients
- Magnetic Disk (HDD) - cheap, slow, bulk storage — backbone of data lakes
- Solid State Drive (SSD) - fast, expensive — standard for OLTP databases
- RAM - fastest, volatile, lost on power off — used for caching and processing
- Networking and CPU - critical for distributed storage systems
- Serialization - converting data to a standard format for storage or transmission
- Compression - makes data smaller, speeds up scans, reduces network costs
- Caching - storing frequently accessed data in fast storage layers

## Main Types of Storage Systems

### File Storage
- Organised into a directory tree
- Supports random reads and writes
- Examples: local disk, NAS, Amazon EFS

### Block Storage
- Raw storage provided by SSDs and HDDs
- Standard for VM operating systems and transactional databases
- Examples: Amazon EBS, RAID arrays

### Object Storage
- Key-value store for immutable data objects
- Write once — cannot update or append, must rewrite the full object
- Massively scalable, highly durable, cheap
- The gold standard for data lakes
- Examples: Amazon S3, Azure Blob Storage, Google Cloud Storage

### Cache and Memory-Based Storage
- Ultra-fast retrieval for frequently accessed data
- Data is volatile — lost if power goes off
- Examples: Redis, Memcached

### HDFS (Hadoop Distributed File System)
- Combines compute and storage on the same nodes
- Used in legacy big data systems and Apache Spark clusters
- Being replaced by cloud object storage in most organisations

### Streaming Storage
- Stores event streams with configurable retention
- Supports replay — reprocess historical data from any point in time
- Examples: Apache Kafka, Amazon Kinesis, Google Pub/Sub

## Data Temperature

| Temperature | Access Frequency | Storage Type | Cost |
|---|---|---|---|
| 🔥 Hot | Constantly | SSD or RAM | Most expensive |
| 🌤️ Warm | Monthly | Infrequent access object storage | Medium |
| ❄️ Cold | Rarely | Archival storage | Cheapest to store, expensive to retrieve |

## Key Storage Abstractions

### Data Warehouse
- Structured, formatted data for analytics and reporting
- Examples: Snowflake, Google BigQuery, Amazon Redshift

### Data Lake
- Stores ALL data — structured and unstructured — in object storage
- Originally write-once, read-many — no updates or deletes
- Can become a data swamp without good governance

### Data Lakehouse
- Combines data lake and data warehouse capabilities
- Supports ACID transactions — update and delete records
- Stores data in open formats in object storage
- Examples: Databricks Delta Lake, Apache Hudi, Apache Iceberg

### Data Catalog
- Centralised metadata store for all data across the organisation
- Makes data discoverable for analysts, scientists, and engineers
- Tracks data lineage, descriptions, and relationships

## Key Concepts

### Eventual vs Strong Consistency
- Strong consistency - every read returns the latest written value (slower)
- Eventual consistency - reads will become consistent over time (faster, scalable)
- BASE - Basically Available, Soft-state, Eventual consistency (opposite of ACID)

### Separation of Compute from Storage
- Store data in object storage (cheap, durable, scalable)
- Spin up temporary compute clusters only when processing is needed
- Delete clusters when done — pay only for what you use
- This is the dominant pattern in modern cloud data engineering

### Schema Patterns
- Schema on write - data must conform to a schema when written (strict)
- Schema on read - schema is determined when data is read (flexible)

### Data Retention
Ask these questions for every dataset:
- How valuable is this data?
- How long do we need to keep it?
- Are there compliance requirements (HIPAA, GDPR, PCI)?
- What is the cost of storing vs retrieving it?

## Key Terms I Learned
- HDD - Hard Disk Drive, magnetic spinning disk, cheap bulk storage
- SSD - Solid State Drive, fast flash memory storage
- RAM - Random Access Memory, volatile, ultra-fast
- Serialization - converting data to a standard format for storage or transmission
- Compression - making data smaller to save space and improve scan speeds
- Object storage - key-value store for immutable objects, gold standard for data lakes
- HDFS - Hadoop Distributed File System, legacy big data storage
- ACID - Atomicity Consistency Isolation Durability, strong transaction guarantees
- BASE - Basically Available Soft-state Eventual consistency
- Eventual consistency - reads become consistent over time, not immediately
- Strong consistency - every read returns the latest written data
- Data lakehouse - hybrid of data lake and data warehouse
- Data catalog - centralised metadata store for data discovery
- Partitioning - splitting a table into subtables by a field to speed up queries
- Clustering - sorting data within partitions to colocate similar values
- Zero copy cloning - creating a virtual copy of data without physically copying it
- TTL - Time to Live, how long data is kept before expiring
- Schema on write - data must match schema at write time
- Schema on read - schema is applied when data is read

